            <abstract>        <p>According to <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/Z26VQJ9A"><seg type="journalArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Nollet1931Mercure"/><title level="a">Les miracles de saint Mercure Philopater</title><title level="j">Aethiops</title><author><t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Geneviève</t:forename><t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Nollet</t:surname></author><date>1931</date><biblScope unit="volume">4</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">20-24</biblScope><citedRange unit="page">20-21</citedRange></bibl>, at least three texts narrate the death of Emperor Julian the Apostate
                through the involvement of <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7025Mercury">MercuriusMercury</persName>. Two of these three
                texts are presented in the form of miracles, known to have circulated along with
                <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7292MartyrMa">The Martyrdom of Mercurius (recension a)</ref>, <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7293MartyrMb">The Martyrdom of Mercurius (recension b)</ref>, and <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7294MartyrMc">Vita of Mercurius (recension c)</ref>, all of which are assigned to <date ref="ethiocal:Hedar25">the 25th of
                        Ḫǝdār</date>. These miracles were translated from the text contained in <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BNFabb110">Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, BnF Éthiopien d'Abbadie 110</ref> by <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/Z26VQJ9A"><seg type="journalArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Nollet1931Mercure"/><title level="a">Les miracles de saint Mercure Philopater</title><title level="j">Aethiops</title><author><t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Geneviève</t:forename><t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Nollet</t:surname></author><date>1931</date><biblScope unit="volume">4</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">20-24</biblScope><citedRange unit="page">22-24</citedRange></bibl> as the "First Miracle" and the "Second Miracle." This record pertains to
                the "First Miracle," here defined as the Miracle of Mercurius: Death of Emperor
                Julian the Apostate (version a). This miracle is attested (e.g. in <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BNFabb110">Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, BnF Éthiopien d'Abbadie 110</ref>) along with <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7303TammeraBishops">Miracle of Mercurius: Death of the Emperor Julian the
    Apostate (version b)</ref>.
            </p>
